{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionTransparency in algorithmic systems has become a central principle in algorithmic accountability, enabling users to understand how systems work, the data they use, and their limitations [11,30].",
    "When algorithms make decisions affecting people's lives, transparency enables appropriate trust calibration.",
    "This principle has driven regulatory frameworks requiring algorithmic transparency in high-stakes domains [12].",
    "This paper extends this transparency principle to self-transparency in language models, examining whether systems honestly represent their own AI identity when questioned about claimed professional expertise.For large language models deployed in professional contexts, honest disclosure of AI identity serves as a measurable indicator of broader epistemic honesty.",
    "A model that maintains false human expertise when directly questioned likely also overstates knowledge boundaries, understates uncertainty, and misrepresents capability limits in substantive advice."
  ]
}